abstract: Does the world belong to them or to us?
snippet: Does the world belong to them or to us?
lead_paragraph: Bernie Sanders wants to get rid of them. Amy Klobuchar is fine with them, but wants them to pay somewhat higher taxes. Joe Biden promises them that under him, “nothing would fundamentally change.” Tom Steyer is one of them and wouldn’t be in the race if he wasn’t but seems slightly embarrassed about it. Elizabeth Warren wants to break up the companies that made many of them in the first place. Michael Bloomberg is trying to become president largely on the basis of being one. It would take Pete Buttigieg thousands of years to become one at his past rate of adult wealth creation, and yet he seems to be their top choice.

abstract: U.S. Senator Elizabeth Warren raised more money than most of her Democratic presidential rivals in the weeks before the Iowa caucuses, but spent so heavily that her campaign took out a $3 million loan fearing she would run out of cash.
snippet: U.S. Senator Elizabeth Warren raised more money than most of her Democratic presidential rivals in the weeks before the Iowa caucuses, but spent so heavily that her campaign took out a $3 million loan fearing she would run out of cash.
lead_paragraph: NEW YORK/WASHINGTON — U.S. Senator Elizabeth Warren raised more money than most of her Democratic presidential rivals in the weeks before the Iowa caucuses, but spent so heavily that her campaign took out a $3 million loan fearing she would run out of cash.
headline_main: Democrat Warren, Worried Campaign Will Run Out of Cash, Taps $3 Million Loan
headline_print_headline: Democrat Warren, Worried Campaign Will Run Out of Cash, Taps $3 Million Loan

abstract: Businessman Tom Steyer poured $64.7 million of his own wealth in January into his bid to win the Democratic presidential nomination, for a total spend of $267 million, a campaign finance disclosure showed on Thursday.
snippet: Businessman Tom Steyer poured $64.7 million of his own wealth in January into his bid to win the Democratic presidential nomination, for a total spend of $267 million, a campaign finance disclosure showed on Thursday.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Businessman Tom Steyer poured $64.7 million of his own wealth in January into his bid to win the Democratic presidential nomination, for a total spend of $267 million, a campaign finance disclosure showed on Thursday.
headline_main: Businessman Steyer Pumps $64.7 Million of Own Funds Into U.S. Presidential Bid in January
headline_print_headline: Businessman Steyer Pumps $64.7 Million of Own Funds Into U.S. Presidential Bid in January

abstract: Corrections that appeared in print on Friday, Feb. 21, 2020.
snippet: Corrections that appeared in print on Friday, Feb. 21, 2020.
lead_paragraph: A map with an article on Sunday about the philanthropic contributions of Michael R. Bloomberg misidentified the location of one recipient, EngenderHealth. It is based in Washington, D.C., not Vermont.

abstract: Many Democratic presidential candidates launched their campaigns last year with bold pledges to reject help from super PACs and dark money groups. But as the realities of a tough primary fight sink in, those promises are fading away.
snippet: Many Democratic presidential candidates launched their campaigns last year with bold pledges to reject help from super PACs and dark money groups. But as the realities of a tough primary fight sink in, those promises are fading away.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Many Democratic presidential candidates launched their campaigns last year with bold pledges to reject help from super PACs and dark money groups. But as the realities of a tough primary fight sink in, those promises are fading away.
headline_main: Democrats Big Money Pledges Give Way to Reality of 2020 Race

abstract: President Donald Trump on Thursday ridiculed the historic best-picture Oscar win for South Korean film "Parasite," telling a campaign rally he wished for the return of Hollywood classics like 1939's "Gone with the Wind."
snippet: President Donald Trump on Thursday ridiculed the historic best-picture Oscar win for South Korean film "Parasite," telling a campaign rally he wished for the return of Hollywood classics like 1939's "Gone with the Wind."
lead_paragraph: COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. — President Donald Trump on Thursday ridiculed the historic best-picture Oscar win for South Korean film "Parasite," telling a campaign rally he wished for the return of Hollywood classics like 1939's "Gone with the Wind."
headline_main: Trump Blasts Best-Picture Oscar for South Korean Film 'Parasite'
headline_print_headline: Trump Blasts Best-Picture Oscar for South Korean Film 'Parasite'

abstract: Michael Bloomberg’s campaign advisers had anticipated tough debate questions on stop-and-frisk and nondisclosure agreements. The former mayor’s performance left his team rattled.
snippet: Michael Bloomberg’s campaign advisers had anticipated tough debate questions on stop-and-frisk and nondisclosure agreements. The former mayor’s performance left his team rattled.
lead_paragraph: Michael R. Bloomberg had put in the hours, his people said — holding mock debate sessions with top aides and meeting at length to prepare in New York and Palm Springs, Calif.
